WEBVTT

00:00.706 --> 00:09.760
God, Father, Son, and Holy Spirit, may the words of my mouth and the meditations of our hearts be acceptable and pleasing to you, O Lord, our rock and our redeemer.

00:10.220 --> 00:10.541
Amen.

00:11.823 --> 00:15.328
So as usual, a bit of context before we jump in here.

00:15.989 --> 00:21.097
Paul's writing this letter, the book of Romans, to the church in Rome, as the title may suggest.

00:21.737 --> 00:30.130
Paul's never been to Rome yet, despite all of his missionary journeys, because most of those took place in what is now Greece and Turkey.

00:30.434 --> 00:35.362
but he wants to go to Rome to visit with them and to proclaim the gospel there.

00:35.402 --> 00:43.636
So at the outset of this letter, Paul's trying to make sure that he's on the same page as the Roman church, make sure they understand each other.

00:44.176 --> 00:52.530
He's never met them, he wants to assure them that they believe in the same message of the gospel and that they are united as the body of Christ.

00:52.930 --> 01:06.514
So in his introduction before our text this morning, Paul makes sure to let these believers in Rome know that he sees them as brothers and sisters in Christ, united under Jesus as spiritual inheritors of the Old Testament covenants.

01:06.534 --> 01:17.714
Paul writes that he longs to see these believers, to encourage them with the message of the gospel, and he hopes that his visit will bear fruit just as he has seen his other missionary journeys bear fruit.

01:18.146 --> 01:19.088
So that's the preamble.

01:19.128 --> 01:22.113
That's the context that brings us to our text this morning.

01:22.594 --> 01:26.181
So let's read then from Romans chapter 1 starting at verse 14.

01:27.163 --> 01:34.456
Paul writes to the church in Rome, I am obligated both to Greeks and non-Greeks, both to the wise and to the foolish.

01:35.117 --> 01:39.465
And that is why I am so eager to preach the gospel also to you who are in Rome.

01:40.166 --> 01:42.130
For I am not ashamed of the gospel.

01:42.562 --> 01:48.449
because it is the power of God that brings salvation to everyone who believes, first to the Jew, then to the Gentile.

01:49.129 --> 01:59.841
For in the gospel, the righteousness of God is revealed, a righteousness that is by faith from first to last, just as it is written, the righteous will live by faith.

02:00.382 --> 02:01.823
This is the word of the Lord.

02:02.564 --> 02:03.846
Thanks be to God.

02:03.906 --> 02:11.474
When Larissa and I lived in Ohio before we moved up here,

02:11.586 --> 02:16.453
My main source of income was bartending at a couple of different craft breweries.

02:17.394 --> 02:31.072
And when we were preparing several years ago to move to Ohio, and we knew that that was kind of where I was going to be doing most of my work, a lot of our friends and our family had a similar reaction to each other.

02:31.152 --> 02:36.600
Most of them said something along lines of like, oh, bartending, that'll be great for pastoral ministry.

02:36.660 --> 02:38.742
People really open up to their bartenders, right?

02:38.762 --> 02:41.426
You'll be able to share a lot of things with them.

02:42.402 --> 02:46.828
And that's kind of the posture that I had in mind as I went into that.

02:46.888 --> 02:47.829
Like, okay, great.

02:47.849 --> 02:51.694
Maybe I can use part of this job as a means to share the gospel.

02:53.036 --> 03:06.354
But what I found more often than not is it was difficult for me to share the gospel or even to talk about my faith even when the opportunity presented itself on a platter to me.

03:07.266 --> 03:17.700
You know, people would often ask, you know, why we had moved to Columbus, and I always found it far easier just to let them know what Larissa was working on and just leave it there.

03:18.882 --> 03:29.637
It was only after a few years of getting to know some of my coworkers and some of our regulars more that I felt more comfortable speaking offhand about my faith.

03:31.760 --> 03:36.306
I, unlike our brother Paul, was ashamed of the gospel.

03:37.250 --> 03:48.924
And I felt ashamed many times when I would go home from work or when somebody would close their tab and leave when I realized I could have shared my faith with them.

03:49.024 --> 03:53.390
I could have spoken a word of peace into their lives from God.

03:53.910 --> 03:57.775
I could have even just asked them about their spirituality or their faith.

04:00.218 --> 04:02.280
Are you ashamed of the gospel?

04:02.581 --> 04:07.026
Have you found yourselves in situations where you know

04:07.170 --> 04:17.303
that you can and should share with somebody the hope that you have in Christ, the community that you experience here in the church, the discernment that the Holy Spirit grants to you.

04:17.343 --> 04:26.655
Even where you know you should ask someone if they would maybe be interested in coming to church on Sunday, watching our live stream, coming to an event that we're hosting.

04:28.878 --> 04:35.506
How much easier is it for us to talk about the weather, the Olympics, other sports, even

04:35.714 --> 04:37.757
politics than the gospel.

04:39.439 --> 04:43.704
A shamed may be a bit of a strong term, but it's true, isn't it?

04:45.126 --> 04:47.189
Nervous, anxious.

04:47.229 --> 04:51.695
The heart of it, as Paul suggests here, is really shame.

04:52.836 --> 04:53.297
But why?

04:53.397 --> 04:55.500
Why are we afraid to share the gospel?

04:55.780 --> 05:00.466
Why are we ashamed of the good news that Christ came into the world to save sinners like us?

05:01.154 --> 05:04.199
Shouldn't that be something that we should shout from rooftop?

05:04.219 --> 05:14.938
Shouldn't I be more excited to tell you about how God has been working in my life than I am to say that your favorite IPA is back on tap?

05:14.959 --> 05:15.840
Why are we afraid?

05:17.223 --> 05:18.064
It's just that.

05:18.124 --> 05:18.986
It's fear.

05:19.126 --> 05:21.470
We fear backlash.

05:21.530 --> 05:23.934
We fear unpopularity.

05:23.975 --> 05:25.938
We fear ridicule.

05:26.306 --> 05:29.430
But our fear can be motivated by good desires too.

05:29.510 --> 05:36.280
Maybe we fear that we'll say the wrong thing and that we'll turn someone off from wanting to go to church.

05:36.360 --> 05:44.010
Maybe we're afraid because somebody might perceive our beliefs and our convictions as evil.

05:44.751 --> 05:55.826
Maybe we're afraid because we have had experiences ourselves where we've been evangelized to or have been around people evangelizing and really harsh

05:56.066 --> 05:57.387
or shallow ways.

05:57.448 --> 05:58.489
We don't want to be like that.

06:01.232 --> 06:14.286
Now if those are reasons why we're maybe afraid or ashamed of the gospel, the question that naturally arises from looking at our text this morning is why isn't Paul ashamed?

06:14.907 --> 06:24.818
Why is he unashamed of the gospel outside of the fact that he is an apostle and so naturally one would think that it follows that he would not be ashamed of it?

06:25.794 --> 06:31.462
The first reason why Paul is unashamed of the gospel comes to us in the first couple of verses of our text.

06:32.403 --> 06:37.690
Paul says that he is obligated, both to Greeks and to non-Greeks, both to the wise and the foolish.

06:37.750 --> 06:43.718
That is why he says, I'm so eager to preach the gospel also to you who are in Rome.

06:45.120 --> 06:50.727
Paul is obligated to preach the gospel, obligated here, meaning indebted.

06:50.787 --> 06:52.850
He owes something.

06:54.658 --> 06:59.205
Now there are a couple of senses in which we can be indebted to someone.

06:59.926 --> 07:02.189
Say, I borrow $500 from Daniel.

07:02.950 --> 07:06.556
Now I am indebted to him until I can pay him back that money.

07:07.177 --> 07:09.580
It's the most common way that we think of indebtedness.

07:10.201 --> 07:16.050
But say, Crystal comes to me and gives me $500 and says, give this to Daniel, please.

07:16.674 --> 07:19.498
Well, now I'm indebted to Daniel in a completely different way.

07:19.618 --> 07:24.685
I am indebted to him until I give him this money that Crystal has entrusted me with.

07:25.906 --> 07:31.594
That second part, that second way, that is how Paul is under obligation here.

07:32.515 --> 07:41.227
He has been entrusted with the message of the gospel by God and is under obligation to share that message with the world.

07:42.889 --> 07:46.354
So too, we have been entrusted with that message of the gospel.

07:46.626 --> 07:52.395
We are indebted to the world just as much as Paul was to spread the message near and far.

07:53.517 --> 07:59.767
The end of Matthew's gospel, chapter 28, Jesus commissions his disciples and us as his church.

08:00.188 --> 08:08.882
Go and make disciples of all nations, baptizing them in the name of the Father, Son, and the Holy Spirit, and teaching them to obey everything I have commanded you.

08:11.266 --> 08:20.357
Now, if Crystal gives me $500 and tells me to give it to Daniel, I'd be pretty excited to take parts in sharing this gift with Daniel, right?

08:21.478 --> 08:25.864
How much more than should we be excited to share the gift of the gospel?

08:27.926 --> 08:31.651
But that's not the only reason why Paul is unashamed of the gospel.

08:31.691 --> 08:41.042
He says, I'm not ashamed of the gospel because it is the power of God that brings salvation to everyone who believes first to the Jew, then to the Gentile.

08:42.530 --> 08:47.437
The gospel, Paul says, is the power of God.

08:48.518 --> 08:49.159
I think that's great.

08:49.199 --> 08:50.521
The gospel is the power of God.

08:50.581 --> 08:55.608
It's not the something that we have to bring ourselves into the world.

08:55.768 --> 08:57.430
It is from God.

08:58.351 --> 08:59.333
It is powerful.

08:59.433 --> 09:03.638
And in that power, there is transformation.

09:05.120 --> 09:06.823
Paul knows this full well.

09:07.083 --> 09:10.868
He tells the church in Corinth when he writes to them in 1 Corinthians.

09:10.908 --> 09:12.370
He says that when he came to them,

09:12.482 --> 09:16.166
He came in weakness with great fear and trembling.

09:17.508 --> 09:30.463
He wrote to them, my message and my preaching were not with wise and persuasive words, but with a demonstration of the spirit's power so that your faith might not rest on human wisdom, but on God's power.

09:32.966 --> 09:36.390
Paul was not always unashamed of the gospel.

09:36.470 --> 09:39.954
He has had to learn to be unashamed of the gospel.

09:40.834 --> 09:43.198
His own life certainly shows that.

09:43.999 --> 09:56.157
Luke tells us in the book of Acts, Paul used to be this great persecutor of the church, breathing out murderous threats against the church, seeking to imprison anyone who followed Christ.

09:57.739 --> 10:07.794
And after his dramatic 180 degree conversion on the road to Damascus, I would imagine that Paul felt a bit afraid, ashamed.

10:07.938 --> 10:15.830
of the gospel, this message that he had been seeking to stamp out now suddenly entrusted to him, to bring to the world.

10:15.890 --> 10:26.146
I'm sure Paul felt afraid that he would misrepresent this gospel messenger, say the wrong thing, turn people off from Christ due to his violent past.

10:27.608 --> 10:31.314
Paul had to learn to be unashamed of the gospel.

10:32.642 --> 10:43.556
And thanks to the transforming power that is inherent within the message of the gospel, we have here in writing in the book of Romans that same afraid man now unashamed and bold.

10:44.957 --> 10:49.623
Paul knows firsthand the power of salvation that comes from God in the gospel.

10:50.124 --> 10:58.194
Because if it can save him, chief among sinners as he admits to Timothy later, then the gospel can save anyone who believes.

11:00.578 --> 11:13.332
So because of this, Paul can overcome just about any temptation to be ashamed of the gospel because he remembers that this message of the gospel, which is foolishness to those who do not believe, is power from God.

11:13.993 --> 11:16.115
That is for salvation for all who do believe.

11:18.137 --> 11:21.441
Now, of course, that call to remembrance is for us as well.

11:22.922 --> 11:29.810
How have we been shaped or transformed by the renewing of our minds to the power of God proclaimed in his word?

11:30.658 --> 11:35.103
How as being a follower of Christ changed us, brought us closer to God.

11:36.825 --> 11:49.599
By remembering and giving testimony to how the power of the gospel has transformed our lives, we too can feel our fears and misgivings assuaged and be empowered anew by the Holy Spirit to be unashamed.

11:51.220 --> 12:00.210
Again, if we go to Jesus at the end of Matthew's gospel, all authority, he says, in heaven and on earth has been given to me, therefore go.

12:01.410 --> 12:05.096
Authority, the word in Greek, exusia, it means power.

12:05.977 --> 12:11.325
All power, Jesus says, in heaven and on earth has been given to me, so then go.

12:12.587 --> 12:19.677
God's power undergirds and supports us as we are sent out with this message that we are entrusted with.

12:21.720 --> 12:23.743
So Paul, Paul is unashamed of the gospel.

12:23.824 --> 12:25.406
He's under obligation to preach it.

12:25.746 --> 12:30.834
He's unashamed of the gospel because he remembers the power of God that is at work within it.

12:31.650 --> 12:39.022
Finally, then Paul writes to the Romans and to us, he says that in the gospel, the righteousness of God is revealed.

12:39.904 --> 12:46.074
A righteousness that is by faith from first to last, just as it is written, the righteous will live by faith.

12:47.617 --> 12:48.879
The righteousness of God.

12:50.542 --> 12:53.927
The righteousness of God can be a few different things.

12:53.988 --> 12:57.874
Paul could mean a few different things, different writers in the Bible.

12:57.954 --> 13:04.082
Pretty consistently, we'll refer to the righteousness of God, meaning three different kind of aspects of righteousness.

13:05.284 --> 13:10.812
The first being righteousness as an aspect of God, an attribute of God.

13:11.413 --> 13:13.175
God's justice, God's love.

13:13.255 --> 13:17.080
Like we can say, we have a God who is righteous.

13:18.162 --> 13:24.050
The righteousness of God can also refer to a status that is a gift from God.

13:24.802 --> 13:33.692
We can say, in Christ, God grants us his righteousness that we may be rescued from our sins and be put into a right relationship with God.

13:34.873 --> 13:41.861
Finally, the righteousness of God can be a reference to God's activity of salvation in the world.

13:43.243 --> 13:46.426
And I think here it's in that last sense that Paul has in mind.

13:46.947 --> 13:49.970
That doesn't mean that the other two aren't being referenced at all.

13:50.434 --> 13:52.036
God is, of course, certainly righteous.

13:52.096 --> 13:56.002
God certainly bestows upon us a status of righteousness in Christ.

13:56.743 --> 14:08.218
But for the purpose of these passages in Romans 1 here, it seems like Paul's referring more to this aspect of God's righteousness and justice as his saving work in the world.

14:09.780 --> 14:16.510
Now, Paul doesn't explicitly say justification by faith in these verses, but that's what he's getting at.

14:16.850 --> 14:19.794
There's this doctrine that the righteousness that we need

14:19.906 --> 14:24.715
to be made right before God is granted to us by faith in Christ.

14:24.775 --> 14:27.720
That kind of gets at there's power of God in the gospel.

14:28.001 --> 14:36.697
That also is why I said Paul may be referencing multiple aspects of righteousness here because God's righteousness justifies us before God.

14:37.879 --> 14:43.890
But in the gospel, this righteousness is saving work in the world is revealed by faith.

14:44.386 --> 14:48.490
As the prophet Habakkuk says, that's what Paul's quoting at the end here.

14:48.530 --> 14:51.473
The righteous will live by faith.

14:52.474 --> 15:03.005
Paul also uses this verse from Habakkuk in the letter to the Galatians, Galatians chapter three, to talk about how we are justified before God by faith.

15:05.007 --> 15:11.794
Paul is unashamed of the gospel because in its message, God's saving work is revealed.

15:12.898 --> 15:24.713
In the gospel, our eyes are opened and we can see our fallenness before God, but also God's immense love for us and grace to us in Christ.

15:24.753 --> 15:26.135
That is the good news.

15:28.338 --> 15:37.810
Paul writes in his first letter to Timothy, he says, even though I was once a blasphemer and a persecutor and a violent man, I was shown mercy.

15:38.370 --> 15:40.693
because I acted in ignorance and unbelief.

15:40.753 --> 15:47.442
The grace of our Lord was poured out on me abundantly along with the faith and love that are in Christ Jesus.

15:48.603 --> 15:51.687
Here's a trustworthy saying that deserves full acceptance.

15:51.707 --> 15:55.853
Christ Jesus came into the world to save sinners of whom I am the worst.

15:57.955 --> 16:06.066
But it is for that reason that I was shown mercy so that in me, the worst of sinners, Christ Jesus might display his immense patience.

16:06.370 --> 16:10.115
as an example for those who would believe in Him and receive eternal life.

16:10.175 --> 16:16.463
And now to that King, internal and mortal and visible, the only God be honor and glory forever and ever, amen.

16:18.625 --> 16:23.652
If we have that good news, why are we afraid and ashamed to share it?

16:23.672 --> 16:34.866
If we follow the example here of our brother Paul, we too can find it easier to be unashamed and unafraid of that gospel as we follow after Christ.

16:35.298 --> 16:41.467
as we take seriously Jesus' commission on our lives for us to go and to spread that message.

16:42.910 --> 16:44.132
I have found that to be true.

16:44.172 --> 16:47.937
I found that to be true in my interactions with people as I was bartending.

16:50.021 --> 17:04.082
God, if God has entrusted me with the message of the gospel to bring it to the world, that makes it easier for me to give an honest response and testimony if somebody says, hey, what do you Christians think about insert thing here?

17:05.442 --> 17:14.580
If the gospel is the power of God and not something that I have to bring, it makes it easier to be able to testify to that in my own life.

17:14.620 --> 17:21.694
Being able to share how God has transformed me, given me His peace, that makes it easier to be more unashamed.

17:22.976 --> 17:27.826
I have seen the power of the gospel turn hearts and minds closer to Christ.

17:29.442 --> 17:33.166
The gospel is God's righteous work of salvation in the world.

17:33.446 --> 17:37.410
It is the good news, and people want to hear good news.

17:39.072 --> 17:44.137
My friends, in a world that is falling apart seemingly more and more, people want to hear something good.

17:44.217 --> 17:48.681
People want to know peace, and we have that peace.

17:50.103 --> 17:57.650
I have found more often than not, people want to know peace, even the peace that is found in Christ if we are honest about it.

17:57.954 --> 18:08.707
If we are confident in sharing that peace, we are often afraid of social backlash or ridicule if we share the gospel.

18:08.747 --> 18:09.868
And yeah, that happens.

18:09.968 --> 18:10.329
It does.

18:10.349 --> 18:11.450
It happens sometimes.

18:13.533 --> 18:19.260
But you know what the reassuring thing is about the gospel being the power of God and not your own?

18:20.281 --> 18:24.626
It is not up to us on our own to convince anyone of anything.

18:25.602 --> 18:28.265
The Holy Spirit will do that through us.

18:29.546 --> 18:34.352
As Paul told the Corinthians, we do not need to be eloquent or persuasive.

18:35.813 --> 18:41.339
Instead, we can be honest and vulnerable and let God take it from there to speak through us.

18:41.399 --> 18:43.842
That's what speaks to people's hearts and minds.

18:47.106 --> 18:54.834
A good example of this is one of my regulars at the brewery when I first met him was a pretty staunch atheist.

18:55.394 --> 19:01.663
He had in his head what he thought Christianity was all about, what Christians were like and wanted absolutely nothing to do with it.

19:03.025 --> 19:14.882
Now thanks be to God over the years I was able to seize opportunities to share with him why I'm a believer, why I'm a disciple of Christ, why I feel called to preach the gospel.

19:14.942 --> 19:17.586
Now he's still not a Christian.

19:18.722 --> 19:34.367
I do pray that God will continue working in his heart, but this guy will readily admit now that in my sharing of my faith with him, he has softened his view of Christianity and expressed some interest even in dipping his toe into church.

19:37.152 --> 19:38.714
So what's the point here then?

19:38.795 --> 19:42.040
Do these three things and you'll be unashamed of the gospel.

19:42.320 --> 19:45.906
Three quick ways to boost your evangelism skills.

19:47.234 --> 19:49.537
I mean, it's kind of there, but not entirely.

19:50.358 --> 19:59.209
Just because I've got a couple of good stories about sharing my faith with people while bartending, that doesn't mean that I'm some great evangelist yet.

19:59.249 --> 20:07.080
I still find myself being hesitant from time to time to talk about the gospel, even though that's literally my job.

20:10.904 --> 20:15.250
To bring this home in a very practical sense.

20:15.650 --> 20:43.282
Last month we had our mission vision values potluck where the deacons solicited some feedback and ideas from y'all about the discernment process to reach our community here in Midland to address food insecurity and loneliness Again, please stay after the service and help us package meals as part of that There was a lot of good feedback that came out of that time, but something that really

20:43.522 --> 20:50.371
Something really stuck out to the deacons and to myself that has kind of helped guide some of the planning and discernment.

20:51.212 --> 20:52.253
So I ought to read that for you.

20:53.155 --> 20:54.616
This is from the feedback.

20:54.636 --> 20:56.479
It says, teen feedback.

20:57.640 --> 21:03.188
Be careful to focus on modeling and showing God's love.

21:04.129 --> 21:11.218
Invite people in, invite people for a meal, but don't immediately evangelize or preach at people.

21:12.418 --> 21:16.224
We want to have a safe space for people to be.

21:18.248 --> 21:23.417
First of all, thank you to whichever of our youth articulated that and gave us that feedback.

21:24.038 --> 21:29.407
As I said, that's been a guide for the deacons as they've been discerning how to minister to our community.

21:30.469 --> 21:38.322
And really, that feedback helped shape some of this sermon because what I hear in that is what I was talking about earlier.

21:39.362 --> 21:47.153
having some apprehension in sharing the gospel because we've seen it done badly or we've seen it done harshly before.

21:47.733 --> 21:59.129
That we've felt pressure to push people into a conversation when they may or may not be ready to preach the gospel at people and not to them.

22:02.073 --> 22:08.722
But again, we can look to the example that our brother in Christ Paul set for us in his ministry.

22:09.794 --> 22:13.440
He writes this again to the Corinthians and 1 Corinthians.

22:14.582 --> 22:22.956
Paul says, though I am free and belong to no one, I have made myself a slave to everyone, to win as many as possible.

22:23.818 --> 22:26.642
To the Jews, I became like a Jew, to win the Jews.

22:26.742 --> 22:32.011
To those under the law, I became like one under the law, so as to win those under the law.

22:32.692 --> 22:36.018
To those not having the law, I became like one not having the law.

22:37.058 --> 22:40.683
So as to when those not having the law to the weak, I became weak to win the weak.

22:40.803 --> 22:47.352
I have become all things to all people so that by all possible means I might save some.

22:49.374 --> 22:53.760
I do all of this for the sake of the gospel that I may share in its blessings.

22:56.204 --> 23:03.954
Paul's posture as can be seen throughout the book of Acts and all of his letters is one of being in relation with people.

23:04.706 --> 23:14.059
Time and time again he seeks to get to know people's culture, their lives, their inner workings, that he can share the gospel in a way that makes sense to their situation.

23:15.381 --> 23:19.587
This is perhaps best seen in Acts 17 when Paul is in Athens.

23:19.687 --> 23:29.842
He gives his great speech in the Ariapagos using fancy rhetorical tools and techniques that the Athenians were used to in their philosophical and spiritual debates.

23:30.178 --> 23:36.168
so that he could better proclaim the message of the gospel to them using means that they were already familiar with.

23:37.510 --> 23:38.852
Christ does this as well.

23:39.172 --> 23:47.826
The gospels are chock full of Jesus getting to know people, eating with them in their homes, getting to know them in their social circles and their synagogues.

23:47.846 --> 23:50.571
They're everyday lives and relating to them.

23:52.013 --> 23:55.458
Jesus meets us where we are, it is often said.

23:55.519 --> 23:57.682
He meets us where we are.

23:58.370 --> 24:00.212
and then calls us to something better.

24:01.573 --> 24:10.101
That is the posture that Paul used throughout his ministry, and it is a posture that allows us as well to better be unashamed of the gospel message.

24:11.503 --> 24:23.094
So as we go out into the world then, let's go as Paul went, let's go as Jesus went, seeking to be able to relate to everyone that we come into contact with.

24:23.615 --> 24:27.058
So we can better speak the gospel into their lives.

24:27.650 --> 24:29.893
Let us be unashamed of the gospel message.

24:29.933 --> 24:38.787
Let us go with the backing of Jesus' powerful authority to go into the world near and far to make disciples.

24:40.149 --> 24:45.417
Because, my friends, we have been entrusted with this message of good news from God to bring to the world.

24:46.238 --> 24:50.264
Because it is God's transforming power that has transformed our lives.

24:51.206 --> 24:56.754
And because this good news is God's righteous and salvific work

24:56.898 --> 24:57.859
in the world.

24:58.020 --> 25:00.203
Let us go and let us be unashamed.

25:01.284 --> 25:01.585
Amen.

25:05.730 --> 25:18.749
Now as we seek to respond to this message today, as we seek to respond to God's call for us to not be ashamed of the gospel, of course we have a few things to consider.

25:18.789 --> 25:22.674
You can grab one of those little yellow slips in your pews.

25:23.106 --> 25:27.733
write down a reflection, some thoughts, some notes, maybe drop it into the offering plate later.

25:29.035 --> 25:32.700
Things to consider, how are we ashamed of the gospel?

25:32.760 --> 25:36.405
How am I ashamed of the gospel in my everyday life right now?

25:38.168 --> 25:44.097
Is there an instance maybe that you can think of recently where you felt the Holy Spirit's leading?

25:44.137 --> 25:50.546
You felt that you were handed an opportunity to share the gospel with someone and you backed out of it?

25:52.834 --> 25:56.861
We can think about what difference does it make to us?

25:57.122 --> 26:02.211
What difference does it make in your mind if you consider that you are entrusted with this message of hope?

26:03.393 --> 26:07.761
Or that it's God's power, not your own power being brought into the world?

26:08.782 --> 26:12.249
That God wants to partner with us through the working of the Holy Spirit.

26:12.269 --> 26:15.314
How does that change your posture?

26:17.890 --> 26:20.974
May you think about how the gospel has transformed your life.

26:21.034 --> 26:22.936
How has the gospel transformed my life?

26:23.016 --> 26:25.279
Where has God worked within me?

26:25.759 --> 26:28.402
And how can I share that testimony with others?

26:31.947 --> 26:36.752
Where is the Holy Spirit leading me to get to know someone more?

26:37.593 --> 26:44.882
Where is the Holy Spirit starting to push me at work, at the bar, at baseball practice?

26:44.962 --> 26:48.242
to get to know someone so that I can share the gospel with them.

